<p>Gold surged past $5,000 an ounce for the first time on Monday, briefly touching around $5,100 as investors moved into the traditional safe-haven amid heightened global and political uncertainty. Several outlets linked the rally to geopolitics and policy uncertainty during President Trump’s administration, alongside broader risk aversion in markets. The Financial Times reported bullion was on track for its strongest month in about 40 years, underscoring how quickly demand has accelerated.</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/NBIw_PfG6F3zstjLctViNM7Iod7JTQrGj1X73MUOOaMwhh8KmXAD3vYhBc7ZRhy6TVgNGIh34dfREnXB06PRaR01gbj9nQWq-cDVwksu01iE53beqKgRsWQMcRrghzeNc29LFGNSvyi6hG6UC4lF3n6qhRSfXTPOlMpd7vVyTmvTYv0kbwfbBgQgH4r809_oCxEzxY5--qIBvzyQ8xomtVrDejJBFY2SPnPjlEGqdGzwlkducrG9MJzJiQ0-juTIosgCSQMr9RPJ4_BauZAm' alt='Gold hit a fresh record as investors sought a safe haven.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>2025 run-up: One report said gold rose about 64% in 2025 and has gained more than 17% so far this year, highlighting how long the move has been building.</li><li>Central bank buying: China extended its gold-buying streak for a 14th month in December, according to one article, adding official-sector support to the rally.</li><li>ETF inflows: Record inflows into gold exchange-traded funds were cited as another driver alongside physical and official demand.</li><li>Tariff signals: One report tied market jitters to recent tariff threats and reversals involving Europe, Canada and France, which it said fed a &quot;crisis of confidence&quot; in US assets.</li><li>De-dollarisation hedge: Analysts told the South China Morning Post that gold is increasingly seen as a strategic hedge as some countries push for de-dollarisation amid geopolitical risk.</li></ul><blockquote>We see the recent move as justifiable, given the rise in geopolitical risks and macro environment - Alexandra Symeonidi</blockquote><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Market analysts (SCMP): Some analysts view gold’s jump as a rational hedge against geopolitical risk and a shifting global monetary order, and they expect the potential for further gains. (<a href='https://www.scmp.com/economy/china-economy/article/3341217/gold-surge-has-analysts-eyeing-new-highs-after-us5000-record-amid-trump-era-geopolitics'>South China Morning Post</a>)</li><li>Market commentators (Michael West/Capital.com): A market analyst attributed part of the move to a &quot;crisis of confidence&quot; in US administration decision-making and broader US assets. (<a href='https://michaelwest.com.au/gold-blasts-past-us5000-to-record-on-safe-haven-rush/'>Michael West</a>)</li><li>Financial Times: The FT framed the move as a surge driven by fears of global turmoil, with the metal set for its strongest month in decades. (<a href='https://www.ft.com/content/14cecaac-2aac-4d49-8564-7260dc762abc'>Financial Times</a>)</li><li>BBC News: The BBC emphasized gold’s role as a safe-haven asset that typically benefits when uncertainty rises and interest rates are low. (<a href='https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cvgd8kj2y2po'>BBC News</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.ft.com/content/14cecaac-2aac-4d49-8564-7260dc762abc'>Gold rips past $5,000 on fears of global turmoil</a> - ft.com</li><li><a href='https://www.scmp.com/economy/china-economy/article/3341217/gold-surge-has-analysts-eyeing-new-highs-after-us5000-record-amid-trump-era-geopolitics'>Gold surge has analysts eyeing new highs after US$5,100 record amid Trump-era geopolitics</a> - scmp.com</li><li><a href='https://michaelwest.com.au/gold-blasts-past-us5000-to-record-on-safe-haven-rush/'>Gold blasts past $US5000 to record on safe-haven rush</a> - michaelwest.com.au</li><li><a href='https://www.youtube.com/watch'>Gold surges to new highs as investors seek &#x27;safe haven&#x27; amid global uncertainty • FRANCE 24</a> - youtube.com</li><li><a href='https://www.theguardian.com/business/2026/jan/26/gold-prices-record-5000-ounce-trump-turmoil'>Gold pr